IR Spectroscopy Data Case Study

Predicting the protein content of meat samples

Objective

The goal for this case study is to predict the protein content of meat samples using IR spectroscopy data.

Introduction

Details herein on IR spectroscopy and the Tecator data are adapted from Kuhn and Johnson (2013):

Infrared (IR) spectroscopy technology is used to determine the chemical makeup of a substance. The theory of IR spectroscopy holds that unique molecular structures absorb IR frequencies differently. In practice a spectrometer fires a series of IR frequencies into a sample material, and the device measures the absorbance of the sample at each individual frequency. This series of measurements creates a spectrum profile which can then be used to determine the chemical makeup of the sample material.

A Tecator Infratec Food and Feed Analyzer instrument was used to analyze 215 samples of meat across 100 frequencies. A sample of these frequency profiles is displayed below. In addition to an IR profile, analytical chemistry determined the percent content of water, fat, and protein for each sample. If we can establish a predictive relationship between IR spectrum and protein content, then food scientists could predict a samples protein or fat content with IR instead of using analytical chemistry. This would provide costs savings, since analytical chemistry is a more expensive, time-consuming process.

There are three potential response variables, fat, protein and water. These are all measured as percentages. The distributions are below:

The predictors are the measurements at individual frequencies (wavelengths ranging from 8501050 nm). These absorbance spectra are plotted below. The full data set is on the left. On the right is a sample of 10 spectra with the associated protein percentage for that sample marked on the plot:

Principal Components Analysis

Because the frequencies lie in a systematic order, the predictors have a high degree of correlation. Hence, the data lie in a smaller dimension than the total number of predictors. We can use Principal Components Analysis (PCA) to determine the effective dimension of the data.

The below scree plots show that almost all of the variability in the data is explained by the first few components:

Zooming in on the elbow we can see that the first component explains most of the variation. With a few additional components we are nearly at 100%:

A table of the components and corresponding PVE values confirms this:
Variance explained by first five PCs
PC PVE Cum. PVE
1 98.626 98.626
2 0.970 99.596
3 0.279 99.875
4 0.114 99.990
5 0.006 99.996

Based on this analysis, the true dimensionality is much lower than the number of predictors. However, this is based on a linear combination of the data. Other nonlinear combinations of the predictors may also be useful.

Data Splitting and Resampling

We will randomly split the data into a training set (75%) and test set (25%). To evaluate and tune the models we will use 10 repeats of 10-fold cross-validation (CV) on the training data. This will give a total of 100 CV estimates of the error for each candidate model. All models will then be evaluated on the held out test data. We will report the root mean squared error (RMSE) and coefficient of determination (\(R^2\)) on both data sets.

The data splitting is done using functions from the rsamples package:

# Split data:
set.seed(4)
splits <- initial_split(dplyr::select(meats, -fat, -water), prop = 3/4) # 75%/25% split for the training and test sets
df_train <- training(splits)
df_test <- testing((splits))

# Create folds for 10 repeats of 10-fold cross-validation:
folds <- vfold_cv(df_train, v = 10, repeats = 10)

Modeling

The goal is to predict the protein content of the meat samples. A variety of linear and non-linear regression models are assessed below.

Linear Regression

The first model to fit is linear regression. The only preprocessing we will do is centering and scaling of the predictors. Fitting a linear regression model on such highly correlated data may not be useful, but this will serve as a baseline to compare some other linear models to.

Training Data

After fitting a linear regression model and evaluating using cross-validation we have the following metrics:
RMSE\(_{CV}\) \({R^2}_{CV}\)
1.613 0.723

Test Data

After evaluating the linear regression model on the test data we have the following metrics:
RMSE\(_{Test}\) \({R^2}_{Test}\)
2.062 0.546

Principal Components Regression

After performing PCA we found that most of the variation in the data was explained by the first few components. If we take these components and pass them in as the predictors in a linear regression model we have a principal components regression model.

Cross validation and tuning can be used to select an appropriate number of components. However in this case we will just use the first five components. Based on our PCA analysis these five components explain almost all of the variation in the data.

Training Data

After fitting a principal components regression model and evaluating using cross-validation we have the following metrics:
RMSE\(_{CV}\) \({R^2}_{CV}\)
1.265 0.829

Test Data

After evaluating the principal components regression model on the test data we have the following metrics:
RMSE\(_{Test}\) \({R^2}_{Test}\)
1.49 0.752

Partial Least Squares

Principal components analysis is an unsupervised approach because it does not take into account the response variable (if any). An alternative supervised approach is partial least squares (PLS) which projects the data onto components which explain variance in both the predictors and the response. These components can be used as the predictors in a linear model which gives partial least squares regression.

We will use cross-validation on the training data to select an appropriate number of components to use. Ideally, the number of components should be low enough that we dont overfit the training data.

Training Data

The below plot shows the results of the tuning process. The RMSE quickly falls off as the number of components increases. After about 15 components are included the RMSE slowly rises again indicating overfitting may be occurring.

After fitting a PLS regression model and evaluating using cross-validation we have the following metrics:
RMSE\(_{CV}\) \({R^2}_{CV}\)
0.633 0.956

Test Data

After evaluating the optimal PLS regression model on the test data we have the following metrics:
RMSE\(_{Test}\) \({R^2}_{Test}\)
0.705 0.947

Ridge Regregression

Ridge regression is a penalized linear model which can often deal well with collinearity. A ridge regression model will be fit to the data and cross-validation will be used to select the penalty term (\(\lambda\)).

Training Data

The below plot shows the results of the tuning process. The RMSE stays relatively constant for lower values of the penalty term. It then increases quickly as the penalty gets bigger than about 0.2:

After fitting a ridge regression model and evaluating using cross-validation we have the following metrics:
RMSE\(_{CV}\) \({R^2}_{CV}\)
1.613 0.723

Test Data

After evaluating the ridge regression model on the test data we have the following metrics:
RMSE\(_{Test}\) \({R^2}_{Test}\)
2.062 0.546

Lasso

Lasso is another penalized linear model which unlike ridge regression can perform variable selection by setting some coefficients to zero. A lasso model will be fit to the data and cross-validation will be used to select the penalty term (\(\lambda\)).

Training Data

The below plot shows the results of the tuning process. The RMSE is lowest for very low values of the penalty. The RMSE quickly increases as the penalty increases:

After fitting a lasso regression model and evaluating using cross-validation we have the following metrics:
RMSE\(_{CV}\) \({R^2}_{CV}\)
1.135 0.863

Test Data

Fit a model using all of the training data and apply it to the test data:

After evaluating the optimal lasso model on the test data we have the following metrics:
RMSE\(_{Test}\) \({R^2}_{Test}\)

Elastic Net

The elastic net combines the ridge regression and lasso models. It can deal with highly collinear data while also performing variable selection. We will use cross-validation to tune the model to select the optimal penalty and mixture parameters.

Training Data

The below plot shows the results of the tuning process. For higher penalties more ridge in the mixture seems to increase the error. For the lower penalties it seems that more ridge in the mixture has little effect. The optimal model has 5% ridge penalty, which means that this model is very close to the lasso model:

After fitting an elastic net model and evaluating using cross-validation we have the following metrics:
RMSE\(_{CV}\) \({R^2}_{CV}\)
1.124 0.868

Test Data

The optimal lasso model set 64 model coefficients to zero, meaning it kept 36 variables in the model.

After evaluating the optimal elastic net model on the test data we have the following metrics:
RMSE\(_{Test}\) \({R^2}_{Test}\)
1.168 0.853

Random Forest

Random forests are a non-linear tree-based method which can deal with complex and collinear data. Cross-validation will be used to select the number of variables to use at each split (mtry) and the number of trees.

Training Data

The below plot shows the results of the tuning process. The number of trees used doesnt seem to have much effect, but more appears to be better. However the RMSE decreases quickly as the number of variables used at each split increases. The models dont seem to improve much as the number of variables used increases beyond about 30:

After fitting a random forest model and evaluating using cross-validation we have the following metrics:
RMSE\(_{CV}\) \({R^2}_{CV}\)
2.017 0.561

Test Data

After evaluating the optimal random forest model on the test data we have the following metrics:
RMSE\(_{Test}\) \({R^2}_{Test}\)
2.542 0.331

Boosting

Boosted trees are another non-linear model that can handle complex and collinear data. We will implement them using the XGBoost algorithm. Cross-validation will be used to select the number of trees, learning rate and tree depth.

Training Data

The below plot shows the results of the tuning process. The number of trees used doesnt seem to have much effect at the higher learning rates. The lowest error seems to occur for a learning rate of 1.00 and tree depth of 1, which corresponds to a single split in each tree used (i.e.a stump):

After fitting an XGBoost model and evaluating using cross-validation we have the following metrics:
RMSE\(_{CV}\) \({R^2}_{CV}\)
1.972 0.567

Test Data

After evaluating the optimal XGBoost model on the test data we have the following metrics:
RMSE\(_{Test}\) \({R^2}_{Test}\)
2.497 0.378

Results

Below is a table showing the performance of each model during cross-validation and testing. The models are ordered by their RMSE on the test data.

The partial least squares model performed the best. The elastic net model is second with the lasso model in third. The PCR model in fourth performed considerably below the PLS model.

Next is linear and ridge regression which are equivalent since the ridge model has a near-zero penalty term.

As expected linear regression performed the worst of the linear models.

Surprisingly, all of the linear models including linear regression performed better than the non-linear models. Its possible that these highly flexible models overfit to the data they were trained on and had inflated errors on the held out data as a result. This is true for both the cross-validation and test errors.

The PLS model had relatively low variance in the CV error estimates which may help explain its superior performance on the test data:

Residuals

Below are plots showing the observed versus predicted values and residuals for each model. Even though partial least squares performed the best on the test data there appears to be a non-linear pattern in the residuals. The linear regression model also appears to exhibit a pattern of over- and under-prediction across the range of the data. For other models the residuals appear to be more randomly spread and there are no obvious patterns.

Conclusions

We sought to predict the protein content of meat samples using IR spectroscopy data. Partial least squares regression performed the best in terms of both the cross-validated and test error. The other linear models had intermediate performance. The non-linear models performed worst.

Partial least squares is used throughout the literature on IR spectroscopy regression, often as a baseline model. See below examples:

  • The original Tecator data paper: Borggaard and Thodberg (1992)
  • Goldsmith and Scheipl (2014)
  • Ji et al.(2015)
  • Frizzarin et al.(2021)

Future Work

There are at least four areas that I believe would be worth further investigating:

  • While the partial least squares model performed the best the residual plot showed a non-linear pattern. It would be interesting to look at ways to allow the PLS model to capture this non-linearity somehow. For example Rosipal (2010) discusses a variety of nonlinear PLS methods.
  • Ridge regression is usually well-suited when there is collinearity in the data. In this case the optimal ridge regression model used a penalty near zero which corresponds to standard linear regression. Why does using a ridge penalty not improve the test error?
  • Why did the non-linear models perform so poorly? Can neural networks or rule-based models do any better?
  • The data also include the fat and water content in each sample (determined by analytical chemistry). In this case we looked at predicting the protein content, but it would be worth redoing the analysis to predict the fat and moisture contents.
